definition.value: A multi-faceted faith centered on a dualistic cosmology of good and evil and an eschatology predicting the ultimate conquest of evil with theological elements of henotheism, monotheism/monism, and polytheism. Ascribed to the teachings of the Iranian-speaking spiritual leader Zoroaster (also known as Zarathustra), it exalts an uncreated and benevolent deity of wisdom, Ahura Mazda (Wise Lord), as its supreme being.

A new religion (in the sociological sense) teaching the essential worth of all religions and the unity of all people. Established by Baháʼu'lláh in the 19th century, it initially grew in Persia and parts of the Middle East, where it has faced ongoing persecution since its inception. It is estimated to have over five million adherents, known as Baháʼís, spread throughout most of the world's countries and territories.

Any of various religions practiced in Ancient Egypt. Most of these religions were polytheistic and centered on the Ancient Egyptians' interactions with many deities believed to be present in, and in control of the world.
Despite Ancient Egypt's physical location in Africa, it is usually classified as a Middle Eastern religious tradition due to its cultural proximity to the region.
Any of various related religions that developed as a result of the African diaspora, primarily in the Americas.
Any of various related religious traditions in the Americas derived from the African diaspora, especially those in the Southern United States.
Any of various related religious traditions in the Caribbean derived from the African diaspora.

Any of various traditional beliefs and practices of African people are a set of highly diverse beliefs that includes various ethnic religions. Generally, these traditions are oral rather than scriptural and passed down from one generation to another through folk tales, songs and festivals, include belief in an amount of higher and lower gods, sometimes including a supreme creator or force, belief in spirits, veneration of the dead, use of magic and traditional African medicine.
Any of various religions originating among Indigenous peoples in the Americas.
Any of various religions originating among Indigenous peoples in North America.
Any of various religions originating among Indigenous peoples in South America.

A polyphyletic term used to describe the diversity of practices in areas generally termed "religion", of persons of Chinese heritage, including the Chinese diaspora. This may include the veneration of forces of nature and ancestors, exorcism of harmful forces, and a belief in the rational order of nature, the universe and reality that can be influenced by human beings and their rulers, as well as spirits and gods.
The direction of something observed from a vehicle, typically a vessel or an aircraft, or from an individual's viewpoint relative to the orientation of the observer or vehicle.
Any of various cultures or subcultures primarily defined by recreational drug or substance usage.
A subculture which is primarily built around cannabis consumption, particularly as an entheogen, recreational drug and medicine.
The culture and set of traditions and social behaviors that surround the consumption of beverages containing ethanol as a recreational drug and social lubricant.
Slang that is specific to, or primarily used within, drug subcultures or is otherwise used to refer to drugs.
Slang that is specific to, or primarily used within, cannabis subcultures or is otherwise used to refer to cannabis.

The use of combined psychoactive substances to achieve a particular effect. In many cases one drug is used as a base or primary drug, with additional drugs to leaven or compensate for the side effects of the primary drug and make the experience more enjoyable with drug synergy effects, or to supplement for primary drug when supply is low.
The state of a subject's or patient's antibodies.
The state of a subject's or patient's HIV antibodies.
A state in which an individual tests positive for HIV antibodies.
A state in which an individual tests negative for HIV antibodies.
Slang utilized primarily within the subculture of barebacking.
Pop music which focuses more specifically on gender identity and gender issues, especially as they relate to transgender people.
Any of various kinds of intimacy which help to affirm one's gender identity.
Research in which more than one method of data collection is used.
Research in which qualitative and quantitative data, methods, methodologies, and/or paradigms are mixed together.
Slang that is specify to, or primarily used within, the bear community, that is the subculture of gay men who consider themselves to be bears.
Slang that is specify to, or primarily used within, the chubby subculture of gay men.
Slang that is specific to, or primarily used within, the Latine transgender community.
Any of various diseases due to an acute infection.
A heterosexual man who has HIV.
A heterosexual woman who has HIV.
A bisexual woman who has HIV.
A nonbinary person who has HIV.
A lesbian who has HIV.
An adolescent who has HIV.
An infant who has HIV.
Literatures organized by continent.
Literature of the Americas.
Literature of North America.
Literature of South America.
Literature of the United States of America.

Roman civilization from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD, encompassing the Roman Kingdom (753 BC–509 BC), Roman Republic (509 BC–27 BC) and Roman Empire (27 BC–476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
Egypt as it existed during the Hellenistic period (322 BCE to 30 BCE), from its conquest by Alexander the Great to its conquest by Caesar Augustus.

An ancient Hellenistic state based in Egypt. It was founded in 305 BCE by Ptolemy I Soter, a companion of Alexander the Great, and lasted until the death of Cleopatra in 30 BCE. Ruling for nearly three centuries, the Ptolemies were the longest and final dynasty in ancient Egyptian history.

Any of a group of Indigenous religions of Mesoamerica that were prevalent in the pre-Columbian era. Two of the most widely known examples of Mesoamerican religion are the Aztec religion and the Mayan religion.

A religion which originated among the Aztecs in central Mexico. Like other Mesoamerican religions, it also has practices such as human sacrifice in connection with many religious festivals which are in the Aztec calendar. This polytheistic religion has many gods and goddesses; the Aztecs would often incorporate deities that were borrowed from other geographic regions and peoples into their own religious practices.

The assembly of most or all of Earth's continental blocks or cratons to form a single large landmass. However, some earth scientists use a different definition: "a grouping of formerly dispersed continents", which leaves room for interpretation and is easier to apply to Precambrian times, although a minimum of about 75% of the continental crust then in existence has been proposed as a limit to separate supercontinents from other groupings.
